    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-10-09T12:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-10-09T12:29:00-05:00" n="689"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d689">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">637.0023/102: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Howell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-10-09T12:00:00-05:29">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 9, 1923—noon</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received 4:44 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>125. My 117, October 4, 2 p.m., and 124, October 8, 4 p.m.<note n="32"
                        xml:id="d689fn32">Neither printed.</note> The President signed the Tarafa
                    Bill this morning. He is expected to <pb facs="0978" n="862" xml:id="pg_862"/>
                    write a letter in answer to Mr. Crosby’s protest. The letter will give his
                    interpretation upon certain passages of the Bill which are not clear. Mr. Crosby
                    states such a letter would make the interests he represents more satisfied with
                    the law.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Howell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
